Multiple sclerosis: it is not only about the medication, but also the will of the patient to fight.
Multiple sclerosis is a complicated disease, and a person with this diagnosis needs the care of a number of specialists: a neurologist, a physiotherapist, an occupational therapist, a urologist, an ophthalmologist, a psychologist, a psychiatrist and many other specialists.
However, it is not only about medical care, for example, women with multiple sclerososis also need consultations, if they decide to have a child, the care of these patients also includes social counseling, recommendations for housing adjustment, etc.
Yet all this is not enough: the development of the disease can be fundamentally influenced by the patient himself.
The more he actively fights the disease, the longer he can work and he does not have to fundamentally change the style of his life.
As doctors point out, the passivity of the sick relieves space for the activity of the disease.
For example, it is proven that regular exercise greatly delays the time when the patient needs some compensatory aid, for example, a stick.
It is important that patients and their surroundings do not succumb to various myths, for example, that the disease automatically leads them to end up in a wheelchair.
That is why the site is created Give a Ching (www.bezmytu.cz), which is supported by the ongoing media campaign Give a chance.
The most important person in the care of a patient with multiple sclerosis is a neurologist.
In multiple sclerosis, the adage is twice that the sooner the disease begins to be treated, the more likely the doctor can influence something.
This is because we have drugs for multiple sclerososis at an inflammatory stage, when the process of neurodegeneration is not yet so strong.
The sooner we intervene, the greater the hope that we will be able to stop the disease and delay the disability, explains MUDr. Eva Medová from the Neurological Clinic of the General University Hospital in Prague.
It is very important in people with multiple sclerosis of rehabilitation care, which most often solves the weakening of the lower limbs or disorder of balance.
Patients are treated according to their individual needs: to maintain fitness, improve gait, strengthen the pelvic floor, relieve swallowing disorders or to improve coordination.
"It's really individual, it depends on the patient's specific problems," says MUDr. Martina Kövári, head of the Department of Rehabilitation and Physical Education, Motol University Hospital.
People with multiple sclerosis suffer from the same disease, but it manifests itself in a slightly different way for everyone.
Rehabilitation can not stop the disease, but it can always relieve its symptoms.
However, physical activity also strengthens the immune state of the body, which is desirable in case of multiple shrimp.
Another positive of regular exercise is the fact that the sick verify what they can do, and this strengthens their self-confidence.
"During the exercise, endorphins are also washed out and a person feels good after him," the PhDr. Kamila Algae from the Department of Rehabilitation Medicine of the University Hospital Královské Vinohrady.
By influening the physical side, we act on the limbic system responsible for emotions.
This directly interferes with the psyche and immune processes and stabilize the disease, he adds.
"Premese old, these patients were so-called saving, today we know that they need a targeted burden," prof says. PaedDr. Pavel Kolář, head of the Department of Rehabilitation and Physical Education, Motol University Hospital.
The goal of physiotherapy is to keep a person as long as possible self-sufficient, including job classification.
Physiotherapists therefore cooperate with occupational therapists to get a compensatory aid tailored to him.
Many patients also need the care of a psychologist or a psychiatrist.
They are in a difficult life situation.
When a serious illness comes into your life, most of the time it shakes people.
They're in shock, panic, fear.
They have to respond to a great deal of health - loss of health.
With such a sore soul, we are supposed to go to someone, not to try to bear everything on our own shoulders.
"I work with them in such a way that in the end they come to the conclusion that even with handicaps a full life can be lived and that multiple sclerosis does not mean the end of life," says psychotherapist Renata Malinová - Schubertová from the Neurological Clinic of the General University Hospital in Prague.
