"Sonogenetics" or control of brain cells using sound waves
This video shows how the sound impulses affect the direction in which the nematodes move.
Scientists have raised worms with a genetically modified nervous system that can control sound waves.
Small nematodes change direction when they are hit by sound impulses that are inaudible to the human ear.
Pulses work by switching cells of genetically modified motor neurons that are programmed to respond to these ultrasonic waves.
Related: Scientists can read and write brain activity using light
The researchers said these worms are a great example of a new methodology called sonogenetics, which uses ultrasound to activate brain, heart and muscle cells and activates outside the body.
Sreekanth Chalasani, a researcher at the Salk Institute at La Jolla, California, told the Guardian that this method could one day replace deep brain stimulation - an invasive procedure in which electrodes are injected into the patient's brain that stimulate the brain. The method is used, for example, to treat the symptoms of Parkinson's disease.
The nematodes usually do not respond to ultrasound, but Chalasani found that the reaction occurs when they are placed in a fluid containing microscopic bubbles.
As he found out, the bubbles amplified by ultrasound waves, which then pass through the body of worms.
Reinforced ultrasonic waves act in the ion ducts of TRP-4, which are found in the membranes of some worm cells.
Thanks to the sound waves, these channels open and activate the cells they are associated with, according to a report by the journal Nature Communications.
In order to control nematodes using ultrasonic waves, Chalasani genetically modified the worms so that some of their motor neurons contain TRP-4 ion channels.
When he used ultrasound for such modified worms, the sound waves were amplified by microbubbles and transferred to worms, where modified motor neurons switched on.
The new method is in many ways similar to optogenetics, a pioneering tool that allows scientists to turn on and off neurons using light.
Chalasani said that sonogenetics could have many advantages over this technique.
Unlike light, which must be sent by fiber by fiber to the desired place in the brain, ultrasound waves can penetrate the tissues without restrictions and be sent directly to the brain.
"We believe that when we use gene therapy and therapeutic viruses, we can target human neurons and make them temporarily sensitive to ultrasound signals used in clinical treatment to treat neurological diseases," Chalasani said.
He added that the method would also find its application in the treatment of muscle cells and insulin-producing cells.
