The symbol of the village came alive.
The wheel of the windmill above Chlum is spinning again after years.
It can be seen from afar because it is placed on a fifteen-meter-high mast.
People from a wide area call it "the fan on Chlum".
For the village with 150 inhabitants, it even became one of the elements of the municipal emblem, which the municipality acquired on the occasion of the meeting of natives in 2010.
"We applied for a coat of arms at the time and of course we wanted to have a fan on the emblem, everyone knows it in the vicinity," Mayor Jiří Mašek said.
The Chlum Wind Pump is a local technical monument.
It is also a bit of a memento of the present: it is reminiscent of a time when local people fought for quality drinking water.
The one in Chlum in the past centuries was a rarity.
It wasn't until 1910 that Chlum's councillors decided to make a solution, which then suited until the mid-1980s.
In the village at the turn-off to Číchov, they had a seven-meter-seater well excavated.
Three years later, the well was supplemented by a metal structure with a wind pump, which pumped water into the reservoir at the highest point of the village, near the local church.
"The construction was carried out by the company Antonín Kunc from Hranice na Moravě with a cost of 2 400 crowns," says the commemorative inscription on the ground-floor enclosure of the mast structure.
The pump after several repairs and crashes of the wind wheel expired in 1971.
On May 7, 1973, a new chapter of the battle for water began to be written: a new water supply began to serve that day in Chlum.
The wind pump has remained only a dysfunctional municipal symbol and a local rarity.
They put the dominant feature at this year's reunions.
It wasn't until 2008 that Chlumsky decided to repair the wind wheel again and put them back into operation.
They had a replica of the original wheel made - reduced in diameter by half a meter.
The wheel was fitted to a mast, but still the same year it had to be brought down.
The manufacturer of the replica did not choose the appropriate material and the wheel could not resist the gusts of the wind.
Then the chluminian landmark rested for several years disassembled under the roof.
Since June this year, however, the bike on a high mast has been spinning again.
On the occasion of the meeting of natives, the village had the replica of the bike be modified and again fitted it to the top of the Iron Tower.
But the wheel pumps the service water from the well only into the overflow blind arm.
And over the summer we completely disconnected it, because there was little water in the well.
It was at least idle.
"We will then disconnect the shaft of the wind wheel from the pump in the suction basket again in the suction basket," explained the mayor of Mašek.
Chlum is not the only municipality in the Czech Republic where the wind wheel has reached the municipal emblem, but it is the only village of this kind in the whole Vysočina region.
They have a similar element in the emblem in honor of local technical monuments, for example in Chvalkovice and Zelená Hora in the Vyškov region, in the Kuželov region in the Hodonín region, Partutovice in the Přerov region or in Police in the Vsetín region.
