The speed on the highways will remain with the old.
Acceleration to 150 km/h was rejected by the House.
On selected sections of motorways, it will not be possible to increase the maximum speed limit up to 150 km/h under favorable conditions.
On Tuesday, the House decided to take the Senate amendment, which refused to increase speed.
The amendment to the Roads Act will now go to the president.
President Miloš Zeman said at the end of April that he would veto the tax-fifty-kilometre speed.
The increase was also opposed by the Minister of Transport Dan Ťok (for ANO), according to which the Czech motorway network is not yet built at such a speed.
On Tuesday, Ťok supported the Senate version of the law in front of MPs.
The approved amendment will now allow, in line with the original government proposal, to increase the speed from 90 to 110 kilometers per hour on selected first-class roads, especially four-lane.
The Chamber of Deputies first extended this possibility to highways, on which it could be driven in selected sections at speeds of up to 150 km/h, but the Senate refused.
Members have now accepted his proposal.
Senators, with the approval of the Minister of Transport, also took out the authorization of the transport police to have the last word when modifying local roads, which are taken care of by municipalities.
The Senate version, which was approved by the House, also envisages that sewerage, water pipes or public lighting cables can be stored longitudinally under the road surface.
Municipalities would thus save on the purchase of land.
Municipalities should also not be obliged to take care of road vegetation along local roads regardless of the owner of the relevant land.
The amendment is also intended to help improve road protection and facilitate the management of towed vehicles that the owners do not subscribe to.
Newly, municipalities could sell towed vehicles, which their owners will not register for within six months of the time after the towing notification.
Municipalities will have the possibility to exclude transit freight transport through their territory on second and third-class roads under the threat of a fine even for forwarding companies.
The amendment also abolishes the possibility of introducing electronic vignettes instead of existing paper vignettes, which will continue to be used after 1 January next year.
According to the government, this will save money for the introduction of an electronic system.
