Xi calls for the opening of the economy to the wider world
It is necessary to open the economy to the wider world to boost growth, said President Xi Jinping to the group, whose task is Tuesday's governance reform.
"China should be involved in attracting foreign investment and expertise and improving open policies," said the central group's head of the overall reform group.
Promoting openings in nascent reforms will give new impetus and vitality, it will also provide new room for economic growth, Xi says.
The leading group has adopted a number of directives, including a negative list of regulatory market access, easing of border control policy, support for state-owned enterprises (SOE) to absorb private capital and the reorganisation of the registration resident system.
The statement states that a negative list will be drawn up in which sectors and businesses that are outside the limits of investment will be identified.
This system will be progressively tested and improved through test programmes.
This step is significant because it will provide the market with a greater role in allocating resources, ensuring the legal business environment and make the market more open, the statement states.
The government will also free up controls on the powers it delegates to companies and makes sure that the companies themselves will decide how to manage their business.
The statement also states that China will allow border areas to discover new models of cross-border economic cooperation and new mechanisms to promote regional growth.
In an effort to open up a state-controlled sector, more areas will be open to private investment.
"The government will not change its policy vis-à-vis foreign investment and will protect the legal interests of companies that are financed from abroad and will provide them with better services," the statement said.
In addition, it will be easier for foreigners to apply for a permanent residence permit or a "green card," thanks to the optimization of requirements and simplifying the application process.
The provision of the rights of lawyers to practice and develop professional judges and the public prosecutor was also discussed at the meeting.
The meeting was also attended by Prime Minister Li Keqiang and leaders Liu Yunhan and Zhang Gaoli, according to a statement issued after the meeting.
New inpatient wards may be established in the Karlovy Vary Region.
According to the Deputy Governor of the Karlovy Vary Region Jakub Pánik (ČSSD), the current capacity of the inpatient wards of two regional hospitals and two private hospitals in the region is sufficient, and partial adjustments should be made on the basis of an agreement between the departments of individual hospitals.
In the region, however, there are also possibilities of expanding care.
For example, in the department of surgical departments, a one-day surgery center could be established, where, according to the set concept, procedures of surgical disciplines that do not require hospitalization for more than 24 hours would be carried out.
In which specific hospitals the workplace focused on one-day surgery should be, is not yet clear.
In the case of the skin department of the Karlovy Vary hospital, a laser center could be established with the possibility of using laser technology for skin diseases.
The concept also recommended the creation of an apalic center that would take care of patients with brain disorders who are in a vegetative state.
Such a center should be established centrally and should be an integral part of the anesthesiology-resuscitation department.
There is also the possibility of camping such a facility in the hospital Ostrov, where similar care already exists.
Another inpatient capacity, which seems insufficient in the Karlovy Vary Region, are the beds of follow-up care, especially the beds of long-term sick treatment rooms (LDN), whose capacity in Nejdek is insufficient and, above all, should be closely linked to acute care beds.
Part of this facility should act as a rehabilitation bed and part as a classic LDN beds, recommends conception.
As he points out, the beds of aftercare are mainly missing in the Karlovy Vary hospital.
There could be used abandoned buildings after centralization.
Last but not least, social health beds are absent in the Karlovy Vary Region, focusing on the treatment of Alzheimer’s disease.
There is a shortage of these beds throughout the country, so it could serve as a so-called Alzheimercentrum for other regions.
According to the recommendations, hospitals should also prepare for the introduction of so-called follow-up beds for which the funds of European subsidies will be released.
"These are beds that will be linked to the fields of vulsuage specialized care and will form a space for the translation of patients after the procedure, for example, after cardiac surgery, neurosurgical, transplantation or other procedures," describes the regional concept of inpatient care.
New services could also be offered in the field of psychiatric care.
